  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Historically, efforts to combat financial crimes date back centuries\n- Initially focused on preventing tax evasion and concealing criminal proceeds\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - United States:\n- First comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global issue\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop AML standards\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- 1986: US Money Laundering Control Act\n- 1990: European Community's first AML directive\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act significantly expanded AML regulations\n\n5. Global Expansion:\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Development of comprehensive legal frameworks\n- Expanded definitions of money laundering\n- Enhanced reporting and compliance requirements\n\n6. Recent Trends:\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency and digital financial transactions\n- More stringent international enforcement mechanisms\n- Continuous evolution of regulatory approaches",
